1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:02,373
If one AI judge plays favorites,

2
00:00:02,373 --> 00:00:05,537
the obvious fix is to use more judges.

3
00:00:05,537 --> 00:00:09,096
Average across a panel, let the bias wash out.

4
00:00:09,096 --> 00:00:11,074
The crowd corrects the individual.

5
00:00:11,074 --> 00:00:13,843
It's such a clean idea that a

6
00:00:13,843 --> 00:00:17,402
lot of AI evaluation pipelines just assume it works.

7
00:00:17,402 --> 00:00:18,984
So we tested it.

8
00:00:18,984 --> 00:00:21,753
Across four frontier models scoring forty responses,

9
00:00:21,753 --> 00:00:24,522
here's how much bias disappears as you

10
00:00:24,522 --> 00:00:27,686
grow the panel from one judge to four.

11
00:00:27,686 --> 00:00:29,664
And here's where it stops.

12
00:00:29,664 --> 00:00:32,319
The experiment is the same one I've

13
00:00:32,319 --> 00:00:34,594
been talking about in this series.

14
00:00:34,594 --> 00:00:36,870
Four frontier AI models — Claude,

15
00:00:36,870 --> 00:00:39,525
Gemini, GPT, and Kimi — each wrote

16
00:00:39,525 --> 00:00:42,180
ten responses to a shared prompt set,

17
00:00:42,180 --> 00:00:44,835
and each then graded every response from

18
00:00:44,835 --> 00:00:47,111
every author on a five-rubric scale.

19
00:00:47,111 --> 00:00:49,387
Forty responses, four judges, blinded labels.

20
00:00:49,387 --> 00:00:53,180
From that grid we can build any panel we like.

21
00:00:53,180 --> 00:00:54,318
A single judge.

22
00:00:54,318 --> 00:00:55,076
A pair.

23
00:00:55,076 --> 00:00:55,835
A trio.

24
00:00:55,835 --> 00:00:56,973
Or all four.

25
00:00:56,973 --> 00:00:59,628
And for each panel we can compute

26
00:00:59,628 --> 00:01:02,283
one number: how much higher does a

27
00:01:02,283 --> 00:01:05,696
response score when its author is on the panel,

28
00:01:05,696 --> 00:01:08,352
compared to when the author is not?

29
00:01:08,352 --> 00:01:10,107
The hope is dilution.

30
00:01:10,107 --> 00:01:13,179
If each judge has their own quirky

31
00:01:13,179 --> 00:01:15,812
bias and the quirks aren't correlated,

32
00:01:15,812 --> 00:01:20,201
then averaging more judges should shrink the bias toward zero.

33
00:01:20,201 --> 00:01:23,712
That's the wisdom-of-crowds argument applied to AI evaluation.

34
00:01:23,712 --> 00:01:28,100
So we enumerated every panel: four panels of size one,

35
00:01:28,100 --> 00:01:30,294
six panels of size two,

36
00:01:30,294 --> 00:01:35,122
four panels of size three, and one panel of size four.

37
00:01:35,122 --> 00:01:39,949
For each, we measured the self-versus-peer gap, with bootstrap confidence intervals.

38
00:01:39,949 --> 00:01:41,266
Two thousand resamples.

39
00:01:41,266 --> 00:01:45,215
Let's see what the dilution curve actually looks like.

40
00:01:45,216 --> 00:01:47,997
At panel size one, the mean self-versus-peer

41
00:01:47,997 --> 00:01:52,368
gap across the four judges is plus zero point three eight.

42
00:01:52,368 --> 00:01:55,149
That's small only because it's a mean.

43
00:01:55,149 --> 00:01:57,931
The individual judges range from plus two

44
00:01:57,931 --> 00:02:00,712
point four to minus two point nine.

45
00:02:00,712 --> 00:02:03,494
At size two, the panel mean is

46
00:02:03,494 --> 00:02:05,481
plus zero point one nine.

47
00:02:05,481 --> 00:02:08,660
At size three, plus zero point one three.

48
00:02:08,660 --> 00:02:11,441
And at size four — the full

49
00:02:11,441 --> 00:02:14,223
panel of all four judges — the

50
00:02:14,223 --> 00:02:17,401
residual self-influence is plus zero point zero nine,

51
00:02:17,401 --> 00:02:20,183
with a ninety-five percent confidence interval from

52
00:02:20,183 --> 00:02:24,554
plus zero point zero four to plus zero point one five.

53
00:02:24,554 --> 00:02:26,541
So yes, the bias shrinks.

54
00:02:26,541 --> 00:02:30,912
But the confidence interval at size four does not include zero.

55
00:02:30,912 --> 00:02:31,961
That's the headline.

56
00:02:31,961 --> 00:02:35,458
Even when you average across all four frontier AI judges,

57
00:02:35,458 --> 00:02:37,906
the author's own vote still tilts the

58
00:02:37,906 --> 00:02:41,053
panel consensus by about a tenth of a point.

59
00:02:41,053 --> 00:02:42,452
It's a small effect.

60
00:02:42,452 --> 00:02:44,201
But it is statistically nonzero,

61
00:02:44,201 --> 00:02:46,649
and it is the floor of what

62
00:02:46,649 --> 00:02:48,747
a four-model ensemble can give you.

63
00:02:48,747 --> 00:02:51,195
There is no magic in adding a

64
00:02:51,195 --> 00:02:54,692
fifth judge if that fifth judge is also an author.

65
00:02:54,692 --> 00:02:58,189
Every model brings its own opinions about its own work,

66
00:02:58,189 --> 00:03:01,686
and on average those opinions are warmer than the peers'.

67
00:03:01,686 --> 00:03:03,435
The crowd shrinks the bias.

68
00:03:03,435 --> 00:03:05,184
It does not erase it.

69
00:03:05,183 --> 00:03:08,116
But the mean across panels hides something

70
00:03:08,116 --> 00:03:11,049
much more important than the dilution curve.

71
00:03:11,050 --> 00:03:14,820
The panels of size two are a clean illustration.

72
00:03:14,820 --> 00:03:17,753
The Claude plus GPT panel shows plus

73
00:03:17,753 --> 00:03:21,524
two point five eight — both judges are pro-author,

74
00:03:21,525 --> 00:03:22,782
their biases compound.

75
00:03:22,782 --> 00:03:25,715
The Gemini plus Kimi panel shows minus

76
00:03:25,715 --> 00:03:28,647
two point zero seven — one mild

77
00:03:28,647 --> 00:03:33,257
self-favorer and one anti-self model, and the net is sharply negative.

78
00:03:33,257 --> 00:03:36,189
The Claude plus Kimi panel is roughly

79
00:03:36,189 --> 00:03:38,704
neutral at minus zero point eight.

80
00:03:38,704 --> 00:03:41,637
Same panel size, three completely different verdicts.

81
00:03:41,637 --> 00:03:45,407
Which judges you pick matters more than how many.

82
00:03:45,407 --> 00:03:49,049
So if adding judges doesn't reach zero, what does?

83
00:03:49,049 --> 00:03:50,668
The answer is structural.

84
00:03:50,668 --> 00:03:53,501
Look at the panels of size three

85
00:03:53,501 --> 00:03:57,143
that do not contain the author of the response.

86
00:03:57,143 --> 00:04:00,785
There, the residual bias is essentially indistinguishable from zero.

87
00:04:00,785 --> 00:04:04,022
Translation: the cure isn't more judges in general.

88
00:04:04,022 --> 00:04:08,068
The cure is excluding the author from their own jury.

89
00:04:08,068 --> 00:04:08,878
Peer-only review.

90
00:04:08,878 --> 00:04:12,924
As soon as the author is sitting on the panel,

91
00:04:12,924 --> 00:04:17,375
even diluted among three peers, the score still leans their way.

92
00:04:17,375 --> 00:04:20,339
This sounds like a small methodological point.

93
00:04:20,339 --> 00:04:21,186
It isn't.

94
00:04:21,186 --> 00:04:24,149
A lot of how AI systems get

95
00:04:24,149 --> 00:04:26,266
evaluated today involves AI judges.

96
00:04:26,266 --> 00:04:27,959
Preference data for fine-tuning.

97
00:04:27,959 --> 00:04:30,922
Best-of-N reranking, where a model generates several

98
00:04:30,922 --> 00:04:33,039
candidates and picks its favorite.

99
00:04:33,039 --> 00:04:37,696
Leaderboard evaluations that ask a strong model to grade other models.

100
00:04:37,696 --> 00:04:39,813
In many of these setups,

101
00:04:39,813 --> 00:04:44,469
the model being trained or evaluated is also on the panel.

102
00:04:44,469 --> 00:04:47,433
That residual plus zero point one tilt

103
00:04:47,433 --> 00:04:51,666
is the tax you pay for letting the author vote.

104
00:04:51,666 --> 00:04:54,629
It's small per evaluation, but it compounds

105
00:04:54,629 --> 00:04:58,439
across the millions of comparisons that shape a model.

106
00:04:58,439 --> 00:04:59,312
Some caveats.

107
00:04:59,312 --> 00:05:02,365
The bias we're measuring is a within-judge

108
00:05:02,365 --> 00:05:07,162
gap on forty responses, not the absolute quality of any model.

109
00:05:07,162 --> 00:05:10,651
Panel composition effects are larger than panel-size effects,

110
00:05:10,651 --> 00:05:13,704
which means in practice the choice of

111
00:05:13,704 --> 00:05:16,321
which judges you trust matters enormously.

112
00:05:16,321 --> 00:05:19,374
Kimi's anti-self behavior actually pulls panels down,

113
00:05:19,374 --> 00:05:22,427
which is unusual and may not generalize.

114
00:05:22,427 --> 00:05:25,480
And the residual of plus zero point

115
00:05:25,480 --> 00:05:29,841
one at full panel may shrink further with more authors.

116
00:05:29,841 --> 00:05:34,202
So this is a floor estimate, not a universal constant.

117
00:05:34,202 --> 00:05:39,000
The structural point — exclude the author — survives those caveats.

118
00:05:39,000 --> 00:05:42,422
The wisdom of crowds works on AI judges, partly.

119
00:05:42,422 --> 00:05:45,083
Going from one judge to four shrinks

120
00:05:45,083 --> 00:05:48,125
the average self-preference bias by about three quarters.

121
00:05:48,125 --> 00:05:50,787
But the last bit doesn't melt away

122
00:05:50,787 --> 00:05:53,068
by adding more of the same.

123
00:05:53,068 --> 00:05:55,730
To get all the way to zero

124
00:05:55,730 --> 00:05:58,391
you need a different rule: the author

125
00:05:58,391 --> 00:06:00,292
is not on the jury.

126
00:06:00,292 --> 00:06:01,433
Peer review, structurally.

127
00:06:01,433 --> 00:06:04,095
The cure for self-preference isn't more judges.

128
00:06:04,095 --> 00:06:05,615
It's the right ones.
